───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  What You Need
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  To access this archive you need:

    1. The private key file (.key) from the intended recipient.

    2. Two free, open-source command-line tools:

         age       https://github.com/FiloSottile/age/releases
         minisign  https://jedisct1.github.io/minisign/

       Both are available for macOS, Linux, and Windows.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Step-by-Step Instructions
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Open a terminal, change to the directory containing these files,
  then follow the steps below.

  1. Verify the archive has not been tampered with:

       minisign -V -p minisign.pub -m ${ENCRYPTED_NAME}

     You should see: Signature and comment signature verified

  2. Decrypt the archive:

       age -d -i <key> -o decrypted.tar.xz ${ENCRYPTED_NAME}

     Replace <key> with the path to the private key file.
     You may be prompted for the key passphrase.

  3. Expand the decrypted archive:

       tar xJf decrypted.tar.xz

  4. Verify the payload has not been tampered with:

       minisign -V -p minisign.pub -m ${PAYLOAD_NAME}

     You should see: Signature and comment signature verified

  5. Extract the contents:

       tar xJf ${PAYLOAD_NAME}

  The files are now in your current directory.
